      <header class="home-identity">
        <h1 class="home-title">Lee Wilkers</h1>
        <p class="home-identity-contact"><a href="mailto:lee@leewilkers.com">lee@leewilkers.com</a></p>
        <p class="home-identity-terms"><em><span class="home-place-note home-cite-note" tabindex="0">realist management<span class="home-cite-note-body" hidden><span class="home-cite-prose">Managing what is rather than what should be.</span><span class="home-cite-refs"><span>Mintzberg, <em>The Nature of Managerial Work</em>, Harper &amp; Row, 1973.</span><span>Brunsson, &ldquo;The Irrationality of Action and Action Rationality,&rdquo; <em>Journal of Management Studies</em>, 1982.</span><span>Suchman, <em>Plans and Situated Actions</em>, Cambridge University Press, 1987.</span><span>Weick, <em>Sensemaking in Organizations</em>, Sage, 1995.</span></span></span></span></em>, <em><span class="home-place-note home-cite-note" tabindex="0">generative friction<span class="home-cite-note-body" hidden><span class="home-cite-prose">Treating tensions and disagreements as information &ndash; the gaps between what people and organizations say and what they do, between what they do and what they want, and between what they want and what they get asked about.</span><span class="home-cite-refs"><span>Hirschman, <em>Exit, Voice, and Loyalty</em>, Harvard University Press, 1970.</span><span>Argyris &amp; Sch&ouml;n, <em>Organizational Learning</em>, Addison-Wesley, 1978.</span></span></span></span></em>, <em><span class="home-place-note home-cite-note" tabindex="0">strategic unplanning<span class="home-cite-note-body" hidden><span class="home-cite-prose">For &ldquo;VUCA&rdquo;-shaped problems &ndash; those with volatility, uncertainty, complexity, ambiguity &ndash; recognizing when the structure defeats planning, and dismantling the planning assumptions before building anything new. Short experiments take the place of plans until the problem&rsquo;s actual shape comes into view.</span><span class="home-cite-refs"><span>Bennis &amp; Nanus, <em>Leaders: The Strategies for Taking Charge</em>, Harper &amp; Row, 1985.</span><span>Bennett &amp; Lemoine, &ldquo;What VUCA Really Means for You,&rdquo; <em>Harvard Business Review</em>, 2014.</span><span>Mintzberg, &ldquo;Crafting Strategy,&rdquo; <em>Harvard Business Review</em>, 1987.</span><span>Scott, <em>Seeing Like a State</em>, Yale University Press, 1998.</span><span>Stanley &amp; Lehman, <em>Why Greatness Cannot Be Planned</em>, Springer, 2015.</span></span></span></span></em>, <em><span class="home-place-note home-cite-note" tabindex="0">human infrastructure<span class="home-cite-note-body" hidden><span class="home-cite-prose">The people, relationships, and tacit work that hold a program together.</span><span class="home-cite-refs"><span>King, Kolopack, Merritt &amp; Lavery, &ldquo;Community engagement and the human infrastructure of global health research,&rdquo; <em>BMC Medical Ethics</em>, 2014.</span><span>Svensson, <em>Humane Infrastructures</em>, MIT Press, 2025.</span><span>Simone, &ldquo;People as Infrastructure: Intersecting Fragments in Johannesburg,&rdquo; <em>Public Culture</em>, 2004.</span></span></span></span></em></p>
        <p class="home-identity-subfields">Health / Science / Policy / Public interest</p>
      </header>
      <section class="home-section home-about-section" aria-label="About">
        <p class="home-nav-heading">About</p>
        <p class="home-lede home-lede-greeting">Hi, I&rsquo;m Lee &ndash; an independent consultant in <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0">Atlanta<span class="home-cite-note-body" hidden><span class="home-rail-prose">The &ldquo;global health capital&rdquo; of the world &ndash; I&rsquo;ve worked with most major institutions in the area.</span><span class="home-rail-aka-list"><span class="home-rail-aka-label">AKA:</span><span class="home-rail-aka-item">the &ldquo;city in a forest,&rdquo; &ldquo;hollywood of the south,&rdquo; the A, Hotlanta.</span><span class="home-rail-aka-label">AUTBKA:</span><span class="home-rail-aka-item">(Also used to be known as) Terminus in the 1830s, the southern endpoint of the Western &amp; Atlantic Railroad.</span></span></span></span>, by way of the <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="The data center capital of the world.&#10;DC stands for data center now if you didn&rsquo;t know.">DC area</span> &ndash; closer to cattle than the Capitol.</p>
        <p class="home-history">Most of my work has been in and around public health and global health ethics, with formative detours through <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="Complex adaptive systems (CAS)">ecology</span> and <span class="home-place-note" tabindex="0" data-note="Complex adaptive services (CAS)">hospitality</span>.</p>
        <p class="home-history">I studied ecology along the James River at Virginia Commonwealth University in Richmond, then spent some time chopping vegetables and washing dishes, then earned an MPH at Emory&rsquo;s Rollins School of Public Health in Atlanta. I worked at Rollins&rsquo; Global Health department for 7 years before moving to the Task Force for Global Health.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="home-section home-history-section" aria-label="What I do now">
        <p class="home-nav-heading">What I do now</p>
        <p class="home-history">Most programs and institutions sit on <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosntds/article?id=10.1371/journal.pntd.0008318" rel="noopener">deep reserves of latent knowledge</a> in the people closest to the work. The reserves hold capacities, potential, and interests that are non-obvious, tacit, and rarely show up in formal channels. For a decade+ I&rsquo;ve helped organizations understand and design for those reserves.</p>
      </section>

